   523вҶ’## Commands
   525вҶ’You can specify (sub)commands using `.command()` or `.addCommand()`. There are two ways these can be implemented: using an `.action()` handler attached to the command; or as a stand-alone executable file. (More detail about this later.)
   526вҶ’
   527вҶ’Subcommands may be nested. Example file: [nestedCommands.js](./examples/nestedCommands.js).
   528вҶ’
      вҶ’вҖҰ
   567вҶ’### Command-arguments вҖҰ
   613вҶ’#### More configuration
   615вҶ’There are some additional features available by constructing an `Argument` explicitly for less common cases.
   616вҶ’
   617вҶ’Example file: [arguments-extra.js](./examples/arguments-extra.js)
   618вҶ’
   619вҶ’```js
   620вҶ’program
   621вҶ’  .addArgument(new commander.Argument('<drink-size>', 'drink cup size').choices(['small', 'medium', 'large']))
   622вҶ’  .addArgument(new commander.Argument('[timeout]', 'timeout in seconds').default(60, 'one minute'))
   623вҶ’```
   624вҶ’
   625вҶ’#### Custom argument processing
   627вҶ’You may specify a function to do custom processing of command-arguments (like for option-arguments).
   628вҶ’The callback function receives two parameters, the user specified command-argument and the previous value for the argument.
   629вҶ’It returns the new value for the argument.
   630вҶ’
   631вҶ’The processed argument values are passed to the action handler, and saved as `.processedArgs`.
   632вҶ’
   633вҶ’You can optionally specify the default/starting value for the argument after the function parameter.
   634вҶ’
   635вҶ’Example file: [arguments-custom-processing.js](./examples/arguments-custom-processing.js)
   636вҶ’
   637вҶ’```js
   638вҶ’program
   639вҶ’  .command('add')
   640вҶ’  .argument('<first>', 'integer argument', myParseInt)
   641вҶ’  .argument('[second]', 'integer argument', myParseInt, 1000)
   642вҶ’  .action((first, second) => {
   643вҶ’    console.log(`${first} + ${second} = ${first + second}`);
   644вҶ’  })
   645вҶ’;
   646вҶ’```
   647вҶ’
