   966вҶ’## Bits and pieces
   968вҶ’### .parse() and .parseAsync()
   970вҶ’Call with no parameters to parse `process.argv`. Detects Electron and special node options like `node --eval`. Easy mode!
   971вҶ’
   972вҶ’Or, call with an array of strings to parse, and optionally where the user arguments start by specifying where the arguments are `from`:
   973вҶ’
   974вҶ’- `'node'`: default, `argv[0]` is the application and `argv[1]` is the script being run, with user arguments after that
   975вҶ’- `'electron'`: `argv[0]` is the application and `argv[1]` varies depending on whether the electron application is packaged
   976вҶ’- `'user'`: just user arguments
   977вҶ’
   978вҶ’For example:
   979вҶ’
   980вҶ’```js
   981вҶ’program.parse(); // parse process.argv and auto-detect electron and special node flags
   982вҶ’program.parse(process.argv); // assume argv[0] is app and argv[1] is script
   983вҶ’program.parse(['--port', '80'], { from: 'user' }); // just user supplied arguments, nothing special about argv[0]
   984вҶ’```
   985вҶ’
   986вҶ’Use `.parseAsync()` instead of `.parse()` if any of your action handlers are async.
   987вҶ’
   988вҶ’### Parsing Configuration вҖҰ
